{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}} {{coord|53|55|08|N|1|51|43|W|display=title}}
[[File:Ilkley Moor Swastika Stone.jpg|thumb|300px|A photograph of the original stone, its replica carving and the view it overlooks from Woodhouse Crag.]] [[File:Rosa camuna R2-3 - Carpene - Sellero (Foto Luca Giarelli).jpg|300px|thumb|The Ilkley Moor design is similar to the [[Camunian rose]] of [[Sellero]], [[Italy]]]] The '''Swastika Stone''' is a stone adorned with a design that resembles a [[swastika]], located on the Woodhouse Crag on the northern edge of [[Ilkley Moor]] in [[West Yorkshire]]. The design has a double outline with five curved arms enclosing several so-called 'cup' marks, the like of which can be found on other stones nearby.
The design is unique in the [[British Isles]], so its close similarity to [[Camunian rose]] designs in [[Italy]] have led some to theorise that the two are connected. In fact, the troops stationed in Ilkley during Roman occupation were recruited from the Celtic [[Lingones]]. This tribe was native to [[Gaul]], but in around 400 BC, some migrated across the [[Alps]] to the Adriatic coast. Some believe the Ilkley Lingones were recruited from here rather than from Gaul. It is possible that the Italian Lingones passed through the Valcamonica region at some point, took on the swastika designs they found as part of their tribal symbolism, and carved it on the nearby moor when stationed in Ilkley.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shedding New Light On Ilkley's Swastika Stone| url=https://sites.google.com/site/martinhickescom//shedding-new-light-on-ilkleys-swastika-stone| first=Martin |last=Hickes|date= |accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref>
==See also== *[[Fylfot]] *[[Swastika#Germanic Iron Age|Germanic pre-Christian use of the swastika]] *[[Western use of the Swastika in the early 20th century]] *[[Camunian rose]]
